ynthesis and likely fault localization\n- Host-level: Hosts are configured correctly; NICs report link up. ARP exists. But hosts show no RX packets, and ICMP times out. So the problem is not basic host IP assignment.\n- switch_1: Data-plane is processing incoming packets from host_1 and forwarding them toward switch_2 (log evidence of packet parsing and egress out port 2).\n- switch_2: Appears to have correct ipv4 forwarding entries mapping addresses to ports (10.0.0.2 -> port1 (eth0)). However:\n  - switch_2 initially reported inability to open bloom_filter.json during startup (possible partial initialization failure).\n  - There is earlier tool evidence of intermittent inability to connect to switch_2's thrift client (could be timing/startup related).\n  - switch_2 logs shown do not clearly include packet receive/forward lines matching the timestamps from switch_1’s logs (no clear evidence that switch_2 actually received the packets forwarded by switch_1).\n- Host RX counters remain zero. This strongly suggests the packets forwarded by switch_1 are not reaching host_2's interface (or are being dropped after arrival to the virtual interface stack before RX counters are accounted).\n\nTop probable root causes (ranked)\n1) Link or port mapping mismatch / egress mapping error (moderate-high likelihood)\n   - Port numbering used by the P4 program or action parameters may not match the host->switch interface mapping in the runtime environment, so packets are being sent to a port that is not connected to the intended physical interface. Evidence: switch_1 transmits out port 2; switch_2 may not be receiving on the expected port, and hosts receive 0 packets despite forwarding logs.\n   - Confidence: medium.\n\n2) switch_2 partial/incorrect runtime initialization or config (moderate likelihood)\n   - The log \"JSON input file bloom_filter.json cannot be opened\" indicates a failure to load P4 table initialization/state that the program expects. If the P4 program depends on that file to populate or enable forwarding for some flows, a missing file could cause packets to hit a drop path (or otherwise be mishandled).\n   - There were intermittent control-plane access errors earlier (thrift connection) which may indicate switch_2 was not fully ready when some configuration was applied.\n   - Confidence: medium.\n\n3) Packet drops between switch_1 and switch_2 (lower-moderate likelihood)\n   - The link between the switches or the virtual networking connecting them might be down or miswired, causing packets transmitted by switch_1 to never reach switch_2. Evidence is mixed: switch_1 logs show transmit, switch_2 logs show table entries but not explicit receive/egress during the same timestamps, and hosts show zero RX.\n   - Confidence: medium-low.\n\n4) L2/ethernet addressing mismatch (lower likelihood)\n   - If the P4 action does not set the correct destination MAC for egress to the host's NIC or sets an incorrect egress_spec, host NIC might drop frames at link layer. However switch_1 logs show hdr.ethernet.dstAddr and srcAddr updates were performed during forwarding, making this less likely than mapping/init issues.\n   - Confidence: low.\n\nAnomalies and notable findings\n- Both hosts report zero RX packets despite switch_1 logging packets forwarded — a clear anomaly.\n- switch_2 reported \"JSON input file bloom_filter.json cannot be opened\" at startup — missing configuration/state file for the bloom filter program.\n- Some tooling calls had intermittent failures (thrift connection to switch_2 at one point; bmv2_table_dump produced a syntax error). This may be a tool usage artifact or indicative of transient switch runtime readiness issues.\n\nSuggested next diagnostic checks (for confirmation only — no mitigation actions)\n- Capture/observe packet arrivals on switch_2 (or run tcpdump/similar on the interface connected to switch_2) to determine whether packets sent by switch_1 arrive at switch_2.\n- Check switch_2 logs around the timestam